posts.name: Chris Gerth
posts.cooked:
Something important to note is the stacktrace. It gives some clues as to root cause.

What I see in your picture:

image 1011×328 102 KB

image 1011×328 102 KB

image 1011×328 102 KB

The error comes about while code is in the middle of Rev’s libraries

YAGSL is doing some burn-flash style configuration on the motor controller, which is why Rev’s libraries got called.

Since the error itself is coming from Rev’s space, Rev’s documents or support is where I’d go first to seek input on meaning.

You can also play the law of averages: YAGSL and Rev’s libraries are in active use on many robots, so root cause is unlikely something to be fundamental to their libraries. It’s much more likely root cause lies in something that is specific to your team, and in your team’s control.

The common non-code things I’d be checking, using the REV Hardware client:

Do all REV devices have the latest 2025 firmware flashed?

Do all REV devices have different CAN id’s, which match exactly with what you have in code?

Is CAN bus wiring good? IE, from rev hardware client, can you “see” all devices you expect on the bus?

Finally, have you updated the rev vendordep to the latest 2025 version?

Don’t assume any of these, double-check them!

If all that is fine, I’d then reach out to Rev’s support for next steps.
